# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bowdoin-college
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] During the Gaza war and genocide, protests on university campuses in solidarity with the Palestinians in Gaza escalated in April 2024, spreading in the United States and other countries, as part of wider Gaza war protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The escalation, nicknamed by activists the "student intifada", began on April 18 after mass arrests at the Gaza Solidarity Encampment at Columbia University, in which protesters demanded the university's disinvestment from Israel.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Over 3,100 protesters were arrested in the U.S., including faculty members and professors, on over 60 campuses.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protests spread across Europe in May with mass arrests in the Netherlands, 20 encampments established in the United Kingdom, and across universities in Australia and Canada.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The different protests' varying demands included severing financial ties with Israel, transparency about financial ties, ending partnerships with Israeli institutions, and amnesty for protesters.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Universities suspended and expelled student protesters, in some cases evicting them from campus housing.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Many universities relied on police to forcibly disband encampments and end occupations of buildings, several made agreements with protesters for encampments to be dismantled, and others cut ties with Israeli institutions or companies involved with Israel and its occupied territories.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The campus occupations also resulted in the closure of Columbia University, Cal Poly Humboldt, and the University of Amsterdam; rolling strikes by academic workers on campuses in California, and the cancellation of some U.S. university graduation ceremonies.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Hundreds of groups expressed support for the protests, and the police response in the U.S. was criticised.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Supporters of Israel and some Jewish students raised concerns about antisemitic incidents at or around the protests, prompting condemnations of the protests by international leaders.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students and faculty members who participated in the protests, many of whom are Jewish, said the protests were not antisemitic.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A May 2024 poll estimated that 8% of U.S. college students had participated in the protests, with 45% supporting them and 24% opposed.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 97% of the protests remained nonviolent and 28–40% of Americans supported the protests with 42–47% opposed.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The protests were compared to the anti-Vietnam and 1968 protests, politically criticized by a wide range of mainstream U.S.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Republican and Democratic politicians, and frequently counter-protested by Zionist and right-wing organizations.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protests, including rallies, demonstrations, campaigns, and vigils related to the Gaza war occurred across the U.S. since the conflict's start on October 7, 2023, alongside other Gaza war protests around the world.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian protesters criticized Israel's invasion, war conduct in the Gaza Strip, and U.S. military and diplomatic support for Israel.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students occupying administrative buildings were arrested at the request of college administrators at Brown University in November and December 2023, and at Pomona College on April 5, 2024.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In March 2024, after protesters occupied the president's office at Vanderbilt University, the university suspended students and expelled three.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] These were "believed to be the first student expulsions over protests related to the Israel-Hamas conflict", according to *The New York Times*.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, which was established to protect against racial discrimination in Jim Crow laws affecting education, was reinterpreted by Attorney Kenneth L.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Marcus while he was working at the Office for Civil Rights of the United States Department of Education to include protections against discrimination on the basis of religion, particularly "when an affected student's 'shared ancestry' would have been treated as a 'race' in earlier jurisprudence".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Jason Brownlee writes that Marcus "subsequently became one of the preeminent advocates for applying Title VI against speech and events criticizing Israeli repression of Palestinians, deeds Marcus considered antisemitic", and advocated adopting the IHRA definition of antisemitism.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On October 25, 2023, Jonathan Greenblatt of the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) and Alyza D.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Administrators at several private universities then suspended their SJP chapters, starting with Brandeis University on November 6, 2023.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On November 14, Columbia University followed suit, and also suspended its chapter of Jewish Voice for Peace.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The state of Florida ordered that all SJP chapters in the state be disbanded.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By May 6, 2024, student protests had occurred in 45 of the 50 states in the United States and the District of Columbia, with encampments, occupations, walkouts or sit-ins on almost 140 campuses.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Thirty-four encampments were established in the United Kingdom; across universities in Australia, beginning with the University of Sydney; and in Canada, including an encampment at McGill University.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 7, protests spread further on European campuses after mass arrests at the University of Amsterdam campus occupation, including occupation of campus buildings at Leipzig University in Germany, Sciences Po in France, and Ghent University in Belgium.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By May 8, protests had taken place in more than 25 countries, and on May 13, approximately 1,000 Dutch students and university staff took part in a national walk-out.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A series of occupation protests by pro-Palestinian students occurred at Columbia University in New York City from April to June 2024, in the context of the broader Gaza war protests in the United States.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The protests began on April 17, 2024, when pro-Palestinian students established an encampment of approximately 50 tents on campus, calling it the Gaza Solidarity Encampment, and demanded that the university divest from Israel.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The first encampment was dismantled when university president Minouche Shafik authorized the New York City Police Department (NYPD) to enter the campus on April 18 and conduct mass arrests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A new encampment was built the next day.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The administration then entered into negotiations with protesters, which failed on April 29 and resulted in the suspension of student protesters.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The next day, protesters broke into and occupied Hamilton Hall, leading to a second NYPD raid, the arrest of more than 100 protesters, and the full dismantling of the camp.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The arrests marked the first time Columbia had allowed police to suppress campus protests since the 1968 demonstrations against the Vietnam War.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 31, a third campus encampment was briefly established in response to an alumni reunion.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Other colleges that had encampments are marked in green, and non-encampment protests are marked in blue.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protests emerged throughout the U.S. in the following days, with protest camps established on over 40 campuses.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On April 25, mass arrests occurred at Emerson College, the University of Southern California, and the University of Texas at Austin.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A continued crackdown on April 27 led to approximately 275 arrests at Washington, Northeastern, Arizona State, and Indiana University Bloomington.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Several professors were among those detained at Emory University, and at Washington University in St.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Louis, university employees were arrested.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On April 28, counter-protests were held at MIT, the University of Pennsylvania, and the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA).
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On April 30, approximately 300 protesters were arrested at Columbia University and City College of New York and pro-Israel counter-protesters attacked the UCLA campus occupation.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The next day, over 200 arrests were made at UCLA.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Hundreds of arrests ensued in May, notably at the Art Institute of Chicago, University of California, San Diego, the Fashion Institute of Technology in New York, and University of California, Irvine.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 20, the first strike by academic workers took place on campuses in California at UC Santa Cruz, followed by UC Davis and UCLA on May 28.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The protests ended as universities closed for the summer.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Many of the protests involved students demanding that their schools sever financial ties to Israel and companies involved in the conflict, as well as an end to U.S. military support for Israel, as part of the Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions (BDS) movement.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some protests also demanded that universities sever academic ties with Israel, support a ceasefire in Gaza, and disclose investments.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Student demands varied among the different occupations, including that universities stop accepting research money from Israel that supports the military, and that college endowments stop investing with managers who profit from Israeli entities.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Student protesters called on Columbia University to financially divest from any company with business ties to the Israeli government, including Microsoft, Google, and Amazon.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] NYU Alumni for Palestine called on New York University to "terminate all vendor contracts with companies playing active roles in the military occupation in Palestine and ongoing genocide in Gaza, namely Cisco, Lockheed Martin, Caterpillar and General Electric".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian protesters demanded that the University of Washington cut ties with Boeing.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students at the University of Vermont demanded the cancellation of a planned commencement speech by Linda Thomas-Greenfield.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] After several mass arrests, the demands also included amnesty for students and faculty who were disciplined or fired for protesting.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The protests on many campuses were created by coalitions of student groups, and largely independent, although Reuters Press reported that they were inspired by demonstrations at Columbia University.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protesters at Vanderbilt University smashed a window and injured a security guard.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In April 2024, the occupations resulted in the closure of Columbia University and Cal Poly Humboldt for the remainder of the semester, and faculty members in California, Georgia, and Texas also initiated votes of no confidence.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Columbia, Cal Poly Humboldt, and the University of Southern California canceled their graduation ceremonies due in May.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 13, the University of Amsterdam closed for two days after renewed occupations on campus.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] After demands from protesters, the University of Vermont canceled its graduation ceremony speaker, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations Linda Thomas-Greenfield.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On June 1, students staged a walkout at the University of Chicago's graduation ceremony, and walkouts at graduations occurred at Harvard University, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and elsewhere.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In April, a pro-Palestinian student group won elections in the University of Michigan's student government.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In August, the student government voted to freeze its funding for student clubs until the university met student activists' divestment demands.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On April 28, Portland State University (PSU) announced it was pausing its financial ties with Boeing, including gifts and grants, over its ties to Israel.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] PSU President Ann Cudd wrote in a campus-wide letter, "the passion with which these demands are being repeatedly expressed by some in our community motivates".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 6, Trinity College Dublin in Ireland agreed to end its investments in Israeli companies that are listed on the United Nations Human Rights Council "blacklist" after an encampment on Fellows' Square was erected.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] This included three of the 13 Israeli companies the university's endowment fund had invested in.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The University of Helsinki in Finland suspended student exchanges with Israeli universities on May 21 after two weeks of campus protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 28, the University of Copenhagen in Denmark announced it would cease investing in companies that operate in the occupied West Bank, divesting US$145,810 worth of holdings from Airbnb, Booking.com, and EDreams the next day.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Three days later, Ghent University in Belgium cut ties with Israeli universities and research institutions, referencing "concerns regarding connections between Israeli academic institutions and the Israeli government, military, or security services".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The university had severed ties with three Israeli institutions two weeks earlier, citing incompatibility with Israel's human rights policy.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On June 11, the University of Waterloo in Ontario, Canada, agreed to protesters' demands to factor human rights into its investment decisions.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In late August 2024, San Francisco State University began the divestment process from four weapons manufacturers involved with the war.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The next month, the MIT Coalition for Palestine announced that MIT would discontinue its MIT-Lockheed Martin Seed Fund, a program that financed collaboration between MIT and Israeli universities.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The Coalition said this was "the first known American-Israeli weapons manufacturer partnership to end at an American university since the war on Gaza began".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Three months later, the Institut d'études politiques de Strasbourg said it would break ties with Reichman University in Israel due to its "warmongering" stance on Gaza.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Other universities said they would consider divestment demands regarding Israel-affiliated companies.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some agreed to disclose their investments and committed to increase awareness about Palestine.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Wesleyan University allowed encampments on campus to continue, and at the University of Barcelona, the Senate voted to break ties with Israel.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 15, the protest encampment at Harvard University ended after the administration agreed to discuss the protesters' demands and to rescind the suspension of 20 students.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At California State University, Sonoma State campus president Mike Lee was placed on leave after he agreed to pursue divestment from Israel "without the appropriate approvals".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 23, the University of Sydney became the first Australian university to accept certain demands.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The university agreed to further disclose research grants, subject to confidentiality requirements, in order to increase transparency.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students at The New School attempted a unique strategy that combined escalations at their encampment and negotiations with administrators.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Rather than accepting that negotiations could continue only if escalation ceased, organizers escalated their protests and then offered to cease that escalation in exchange for other concessions during negotiations, improving their bargaining position.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Though police ultimately swept their encampment, the sweep led to backlash and condemnation by faculty and deans and required a day-long shutdown of the campus.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students at The New School secured the formation of an advisory investment committee and a subsequent trustee vote on investment in the fall.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The authorization did not guarantee a strike, but allowed the executive board to call one at any time.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Strike action began at UC Santa Cruz on May 20.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Union members and leaders said they were not teaching or grading, were withholding data, and would continue to do so until they reached a deal with university officials.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The strike was in part a protest against arrests of pro-Palestinian protesters at UCLA, UC Irvine, and UC San Diego.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The UC system responded by seeking an injunction against the union, declaring the walkout illegal.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 23, the California Public Employment Relations Board denied the injunction.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The walkout extended to UCLA and UC Davis on May 28, with the intention of expanding to UC Santa Barbara, UC San Diego, and UC Irvine starting the week of June 3.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Participants included students, faculty, and unaffiliated people of various backgrounds, including Jews and Muslims.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian activists at Columbia said their movement is anti-Zionist, and several campus protests were organized by anti-Zionist groups.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some of the protests were organized by groups such as Students for Justice in Palestine (SJP), Jewish Voice for Peace, IfNotNow, and the Young Democratic Socialists of America.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protesters also identified a wide range of other ideologies that motivated them, such as anti-racism, intersectionality, anti-colonialism, anti-imperialism, police and prison abolitionism, eco-socialism, indigenous rights, and freedom of expression.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protesters also criticized President Joe Biden and his administration's support for Israel.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] As part of the occupations, protesters hosted teach-ins, interfaith prayer, and musical performances.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some protests invited people to tour or speak, such as Palestinian photojournalist Motaz Azaiza, who was invited to and visited Columbia's protest.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The Palestinian activist Linda Sarsour said, "These young people are reaffirming and demonstrating that the tide is shifting on Palestine, that the Palestinian people have solidarity not just across the United States of America, but across the world".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At Columbia, protesters who breached Hamilton Hall wrote revolutionary slogans (e.g., "Political power comes from the barrel of a gun") on blackboards.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] One group involved in the protest movement, Columbia University Apartheid Divest, grew more supportive of armed resistance led by Hamas and the October 7 attacks over the course of 2024.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Within Our Lifetime leader Nerdeen Kiswani, who arrived at the Columbia encampment in April, called for Palestine liberation "'by any means necessary', including armed resistance".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Her group formed from CUNY SJP, which targeted the Brooklyn Museum in May 2024.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Many anti-Zionist protesters donned masks and keffiyehs, which increased concerns from provosts and deans that outsiders had infiltrated protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protesters expressed fears of receiving reputational and professional harm from identification.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Concern was raised about the presence of outside groups at protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] During arrests in New York on May 2, police announced that nearly half of those arrested at Columbia and CCNY were unaffiliated with either school.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Mayor Eric Adams said that they had seen evidence that outside agitators and "professionals" such as Lisa Fithian and the wife of Sami Al-Arian had given students tactical knowledge and training to escalate their protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A University of Texas at Austin official said half of the rule breakers detained at a protest on April 24, 2024, were unaffiliated with the school.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In 2025, Swarthmore College said there was a "growing presence of individuals unaffiliated with the College" and campus property had been vandalized.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In October 2025, Syracuse University chancellor Kent Syverud said the protests on campus seemed to have been encouraged by Iran.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] He emphasized that, although there was an initially welcoming atmosphere for both pro-Israel and pro-Palestinian activities, a noticeable shift occurred later.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Syverud expressed his belief that Iran played a significant role in fostering the demonstrations, claiming that there was little to no involvement from the university's own students in the protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Experts raised concern about far-right groups attempting to infiltrate protests to cause harm, and subsequent reactions from militant far-left activists aligned with the anti-fascist movement.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Qatar reportedly contributed $4.7 billion to U.S. academic institutions between 2001 and 2021; Kenneth Marcus of the Brandeis Center suggested this may have affected university administrators' willingness to impose discipline.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Far-right agitators and white nationalists were identified at some protests seeking to sow chaos and violence, and at the UCLA campus occupation, they were among pro-Israeli counter-protesters who attacked the encampment.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A white supremacist affiliated with the Proud Boys was among the counter-protesters supported by far-right activists nationwide.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On October 25, Jonathan Greenblatt of the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) and Alyza D.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The website Canary Mission published profiles of students and faculty members it considers antisemitic, and Betar US, a Zionist group, compiled a list of students to be deported.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Several protests were criticized for alleged antisemitism.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some students called some of the incidents reported at protests and on campus "threatening" and said they made them feel unsafe.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Jewish students were targeted for their faith, for wearing Jewish symbols, or were accused of being Zionists and subsequently targeted.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some Jewish students also said the protests created a climate of fear and hate on campus.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to *The Jewish Post*, a survey by Hillel of Jewish students at universities with encampments found that most of them felt unsafe due to encampments.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 72% of respondents wanted them dismantled and 61% considered language used at the protests antisemitic.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Department of Education concluded that University of Michigan and CUNY failed to assess whether the protests made the environment hostile.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Supporters of Israel and some students said that the word "intifada", the phrase "from the river to the sea", and chants comparing Israel and Zionism to Nazism were antisemitic.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Others, including Jewish students, argued against conflating antisemitism with anti-Zionism, and said the charge was used to chill debate.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian and Jewish student protesters said that the protests were not antisemitic.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] *The Guardian* noted that incidents of antisemitism appeared to be "relatively isolated" and likelier to occur when non-students were in a parallel protest.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian student groups at the protests were quick to condemn inflammatory remarks.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some pro-Palestinian Jewish students said they faced antisemitism from pro-Israel activists.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some commentators and politicians, including Mayor Eric Adams, U.S.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Representative Virginia Foxx, and NYPD deputy commissioner of operations Kaz Daughtry, promoted a conspiracy theory that George Soros or some other anonymous figure funded the protest encampments by buying the same brand of tents for many protesters.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In fact, the similar appearance of many encampment tents was due to online retailers' discounts and promotions of particular products.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In fall 2024, chants such as "Divest!" and "Ceasefire now!" reportedly evolved towards more explicitly endorsing Hamas, Hezbollah, and Houthis.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some protesters used slogans such as "Glory to the resistance!", called the October 7 attacks "Al-Aqsa flood", celebrated Yahya Sinwar, and used the Hamas inverted red triangle.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Aidan Herzlinger, vice president of Baruch College's Hillel chapter, said students who attended a Hillel banquet at the college were called "baby killers" and "terrorists".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In November 2024, hundreds of posters depicting faculty members as "wanted" were spread across the University of Rochester campus.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some of the posters accused a Jewish faculty member of ethnic cleansing and contributing to the displacement of Palestinians; others accused a faculty member of racism, hate speech, and intimidation.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] University President Sarah Mangelsdorf called the incident an act of antisemitism.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian protesters and their allies criticized the disposition of many university administrations as perpetuating a "Palestine exception" to academic freedom.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian students and their allies raised concerns about anti-Palestinianism and Islamophobia.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Department of Education were opened at Columbia, Emory University, the University of North Carolina, and at Umass Amherst over their administrations' response to student protests and advocacy since the start of the war.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In May 2024, the New York City Police Department shared images of items it said it had confiscated from a protest at NYU, including "gas masks, ear plugs, helmets, goggles, tape, hammers, knives, ropes, and a book on TERRORISM" that were taken from a student's backpack.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] One pamphlet read, "Death to America!" According to the Anti-Defamation League, on the first anniversary of the October 7 attacks, many of the over 100 protests included chants and other messages "filled with support for terrorist organizations" and symbols such as paragliders.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Demonstrators at Columbia published a statement calling on students "to propagate the successes of the heroic Palestinian armed resistance in weakening Israel and U.S. imperialism and inspiring anti-imperialist struggles around the world".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A study by the Armed Conflict Location and Event Data Project (ACLED) found that 97% of protests were nonviolent and nearly half of those that became violent involved protesters fighting with law enforcement during police interventions.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The guard was out of work for two weeks as a result of injuries.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The students denied using violence, calling their protest peaceful.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students and student journalists also faced violence at the hands of counter-protesters.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] One protester at Columbia was arrested and hospitalized after a counter-protester rammed his car into a group of picketers.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Counter-protesters at the University of Pennsylvania approached the encampment with knives, and in a separate incident sprayed a chemical mixture on protesters' tents, food, and belongings.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 1, 2024, around 10:50 PM, a pro-Israeli group attacked the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA) pro-Palestinian protesters' camp for nearly four hours, attempting to breach the barricades surrounding it.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The attackers, reported to have come from outside campus, carried Israeli flags and assaulted students with sticks, stones, poles, metal fencing, and pepper spray.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] They played loud audio of a child crying, threw wood and a metal barrier into the camp, and threw at least six fireworks into the encampment, including one directly at a group of protesters carrying injured people.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A video investigation suggested pro-Palestinian protesters did not initiate any confrontation but acted in defense.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The counter-protesters called for a "Second Nakba", referring to the ethnic cleansing of Palestinians in 1948, and played the Israeli national anthem and Harbu Darbu on loudspeakers during the attack.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to *The Guardian*, counter-protesters included several far-right activists involved in anti-LGBTQ+ and anti-vaccine campaigning.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At Portland State, protesters damaged computers and furniture during their occupation of the campus library.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At Columbia, protesters shattered windows during their occupation of Hamilton Hall.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Police and city workers destroyed students' tents, flags and other encampment supplies while disbanding the encampment at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At George Washington University, protesters defaced a statue of its namesake, President George Washington.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The statue was wrapped with Palestinian scarves and flags, with the words "Genocidal Warmonger University" spray-painted on its base.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students replaced U.S. flags with Palestinian flags on flagpoles at several universities.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In Harvard Yard, student demonstrators affixed three Palestinian flags atop the John Harvard statue on April 27.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The replacement of U.S. flags sparked outrage from some officials, such as New York Mayor Eric Adams.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In response, university administrations and law enforcement agencies intervened to take down the Palestinian flags and reinstate U.S. flags to their original positions.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] With over 3,100 protesters arrested, universities suspended and expelled student protesters, in some cases evicting them from campus housing, and relied on police to forcibly disband occupations.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Most universities that faced encampment protests in the spring attempted to negotiate a disbandment of the encampments, often threatening police sweeps to force an agreement.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Many universities initiated disciplinary proceedings against protesters, accusing them of breaking student codes of conduct.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In July 2025, Columbia University disciplined at least 70 students who took part in campus protests with probation, suspensions, degree revocations, and expulsions.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Police departments employed a range of tactics, including dispersing crowds using horses and police in riot gear, deploying pepper balls, using tasers, mass arrests, and tear gas, clearing unauthorized encampments, and beating both students and professors.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Police also assaulted, arrested and restricted access for some journalists while they were covering the protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some Democrats and human rights organizations criticized the police response.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By fall 2024, many universities had strengthened their restrictions on protests, including more than 100 colleges and universities, and several schools had banned camping on their grounds.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Over 200 groups expressed support for the protests, as well as U.S.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Senator Bernie Sanders, various members of Congress, several labor unions, hundreds of university staff in the United Kingdom, and Iran's supreme leader Ali Khamenei.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protests were condemned by leaders including President Joe Biden, Prime Minister of the Netherlands Mark Rutte, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, and Australian Prime Minister Anthony Albanese.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] UK Prime Minister Rishi Sunak and Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau raised concerns.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Numerous U.S. corporate leaders announced that they wished to know the protesters' names in order to prevent them from working in their firms.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Among them were Davis Polk & Wardwell, Pershing Square Capital Management, shopping club FabFitFun, health tech startup EasyHealth, Dovehill Capital Management, and restaurant chain Sweetgreen.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A May 2024 divestment referendum at DePaul University returned a 91% vote in favor of divestment.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In April 2024, Columbia College voted on three divestment questions.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The first asked whether Columbia should divest from Israel, the second asked whether it should cancel the Tel Aviv Global Center program, and the third asked whether Columbia should end its dual degree program with Tel Aviv University.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The motions passed by 76%, 68%, and 65%, respectively, with 40% voter participation.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students at the University of Pennsylvania voted 73% in favor of disclosing all investments in the school's endowment and 63% in favor of ending the university's relationship with Ghost Robotics, with 22% voter participation.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to a YouGov poll released on May 3, 2024, 47% of Americans opposed the campus protests and 28% supported them.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] American Muslims supported the protests by 75% to 14% while Jewish Americans opposed them by 72% to 18%.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Adults under 45 were more likely to support them than older adults.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 33% believed the response to the protests was not harsh enough, 16% believed it was too harsh, and 20% believed the response was about right.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 48% of Americans over 45 believed the response was not harsh enough, compared to only 16% under 45.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to an Axios poll released on May 7, 2024, 8% of college students participated in the protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 34% blame Hamas, 19% blame Netanyahu, 12% blame the Israeli people, and 12% blame Biden for the destruction in Gaza.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 81% of students supported holding protesters accountable for destroyed property and illegally occupied buildings, 67% considered occupying campus buildings unacceptable, 58% considered refusal to disperse unacceptable, and 90% opposed blocking pro-Israel students.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students were more likely to support the pro-Palestinian encampments, with 45% who supported them strongly or moderately, 30% neutral, and 24% strongly or mildly opposed.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Among those who participated in anti-Israeli protests, 58% said they would not be friends with someone who had marched for Israel, while 64% of students who marched in favor of Israel said they would still be friends with anti-Israeli protesters.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Overall, 40% approved and 42% disapproved of the protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In Canada, 19% of respondents supported the protesters and 48% of respondents opposed the protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] *The New York Times* reported that some scholars considered the protests starkly different from those against the Vietnam War or apartheid South Africa.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to Timothy Naftali, protests against Vietnam in the 1960s did not result in a constituency that felt attacked as an ethnicity, and that the pro-Palestinian demonstrations created "a feeling of insecurity in a much bigger way than the antiwar demonstrations during Vietnam did".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft said current college protests contain "further echoes of the forces that helped give rise to the Nazis", while Columbia University's Chabad chapter said that phrases like "Go back to Poland" and "stop killing children" had been yelled at Jewish students.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In May 2024, some Jewish students on campus said they believed that support for Israel was a "litmus test" leading to their exclusion from campus social life.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In September 2024, after many harassment complaints, the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign banned the ostracism of Jewish students from school clubs for identifying as Zionist.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Far-right influencers and some Republicans portrayed the protests as violent, a "Marxist takeover," and "terrorism".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] *The New York Times* opined that the protests came during a presidential election year in which Democrats had "harnessed promises of stability and normalcy to win critical recent elections" and that the protests were a messaging opportunity for Republicans to divide Democrats.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The newspaper also published an article citing NewsGuard, the Institute for Strategic Dialogue, the Foundation for Defense of Democracies, the Australian Strategic Policy Institute, and Recorded Future on how the media of Russia, China, and Iran had covered the events.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] It concluded that those countries had made overt and covert efforts to capitalize on the protests to denigrate democracy, inflame partisan tensions, criticize Biden ahead of the 2024 presidential election, support Trump, and express support for Hamas and Palestinians generally.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A *Jewish Currents* editor described the movement as providing "cover for the right to expand its attack on protest" in reference to the "draconian" crackdown on protests, saying the "attacks on academic freedom and free speech on campus" were led by right-wingers.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Republicans used antisemitic tropes when denouncing protests as antisemitic, including allusions to conspiracies around George Soros and invoking globalists.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In May 2025, *The New York Times* found that the second Trump administration had called for or implemented over half the proposals of The Heritage Foundation's Project Esther, a conservative program to suppress pro-Palestinian protests and what it classifies as antisemitism.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Initially, *The New York Times* wrote that protests outside the U.S. were "sporadic and smaller, and none [started] a wider student movement".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The "partisan political context" was given as a reason for the intensity of protests in the U.S.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Columbia's status as an Ivy League school, its proximity to New York City and national news media, and its large population of Jewish students were described as fueling increased media attention and political scrutiny that helped spread the protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to a *Washington Monthly* study in May, pro-Palestinian demonstrations and encampments were more prevalent at elite U.S. universities.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 3, NPR described the protests abroad as "a growing global student movement", with student protests in the United Kingdom focused on "an increasingly high-profile nationwide campaign to end British arms exports to Israel".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to NBC News, the protests abroad inspired by protests in the U.S. did not have the intensity of U.S. protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By May 7, protests had escalated in Europe after mass arrests at the University of Amsterdam, with occupations of campus buildings in Germany, France, and Belgium, and encampments on several European campuses.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The Associated Press described protests at Sciences Po in Paris as "echoing similar encampments and solidarity demonstrations across the United States".
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By May 9, protests were widespread at universities in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Sri Lanka, while smaller ones were held at Japanese and South Korean universities.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Media coverage of the protests was criticized as sensationalized and failing to focus on the protesters' demands and grievances.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Dana Bash was criticized for likening college protests to the rise of antisemitism in the 1930s in Europe.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The lack of student protesters' voices in most national media coverage was also criticized.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Student reporters, in particular, were praised for their work covering the protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The global wave of student- and staff-led demonstrations on university campuses continued in 2025, with protests at hundreds of campuses in North America, Europe, Australia, Africa, and Asia.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Inspired by the anti-apartheid and Vietnam War campus protests, students and faculty called for divestment, academic boycott, and institutional transparency about ties to Israel and military contractors.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The movement intensified in 2025 after Israel's offensive in Rafah and renewed violence in Gaza, as well as solidarity actions in response to police crackdowns on US campuses.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the United States, at Columbia University, there were renewed encampments and building occupations, including the occupation of Butler Library ("Basel Al-Araj Popular University").
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] There were mass arrests by the NYPD and over 100 students were suspended or barred from campus.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In July 2025, Columbia disciplined at least 70 students who took part in campus protests, with punishments including probation, suspensions, degree revocations, and expulsions.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] At the University of Washington, protesters occupied an engineering building, demanding an end to ties with Boeing over its military contracts.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] More than 30 protesters were arrested after police intervention.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Thirty-four people were arrested inside the School of Engineering building and over $1 million in damage was done to the structure.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In Canada, after a three-day student protest that included blockades and vandalism, the Quebec Superior Court issued a 10-day injunction barring pro-Palestinian protesters at McGill University from obstructing campus access or disrupting academic activities.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Citing threats to safety and academic continuity, McGill sought legal intervention amid calls for divestment from companies linked to Israel.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] It has also initiated steps to sever ties with the undergraduate student union over its alleged failure to distance itself from disruptive activism.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In Germany, Berlin police cleared a protest in April 2025 at Humboldt University, where 89 pro-Palestinian demonstrators had occupied a lecture hall to oppose the planned deportation of four international students accused of participating in violent protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The police launched around 100 criminal investigations related to the occupation, citing vandalism, use of incendiary objects, and alleged extremist symbols.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The university justified police intervention partly due to banners denying Israel's right to exist, an issue sensitive in Germany due to its post-Holocaust commitment to supporting Israel.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Germany is facing criticism for issuing orders to deport four pro-Palestinian activists who have been convicted of no crimes.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the Netherlands there were occupations and encampments at the University of Amsterdam, Utrecht University, Radboud University, and others.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Several protests were met with police intervention, with students sustaining injuries.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the United Kingdom, members of Oxford Action for Palestine occupied the Radcliffe Camera, protesting the alleged complicity of the University of Oxford in Israeli military actions in Gaza and the West Bank and accusing the institution of cutting off dialogue.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The university condemned the disruption, citing safety concerns, and said it was working to remove the protesters, who had renamed the library after a Palestinian political figure linked to a group several Western governments have designated a terrorist organization.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] At the University of Glasgow, students from the Justice for Palestine Society disrupted campus events in April, calling for divestment from arms companies accused of complicity in what they describe as genocide in Gaza.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Across the UK, over 100 students and staff have faced disciplinary action, with some universities reportedly working with private intelligence firms to monitor protests.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Many universities called on police to clear encampments and occupations, resulting in mass arrests and suspensions of students and faculty.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Some institutions agreed to partial demands, including publishing lists of ties to Israeli entities or freezing select partnerships.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The US government threatened funding cuts to universities that did not address alleged antisemitism or campus unrest, and some protesters faced deportation proceedings.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Civil liberties groups and faculty organizations expressed concern over free speech, academic freedom, and the militarization of campus policing.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In July 2025, Columbia University disciplined at least 70 students who took part in campus protests, with punishments including probation, suspensions, degree revocations, and expulsions.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In Canada, after pro-Palestinian protests at the University of Toronto and a more than 60-day encampment on its St.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] George campus, the University of Toronto Faculty Association (UTFA) voted to divest from Israel, citing its opposition to what it called Israel's "illegal occupation" of Palestinian territories.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The motion, which passed with 52% support, urges the Ontario University Pension Plan to swiftly divest from entities linked to the occupation or arms production potentially used by Israel in Palestine, aligning the move with the university’s existing divestment policy on Russia.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the Netherlands, the University of Amsterdam, Tilburg University, Utrecht University, Erasmus University Rotterdam, and Radboud University have cut ties with nine Israeli institutes, with some also suspending future collaborations.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the UK, King’s College Cambridge announced divestment from arms and companies involved in the Israeli occupation.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In Ireland, Trinity College Dublin severed all ties with Israeli universities and companies, becoming the first Irish university to fully divest.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] This includes ending investments, commercial relations, academic collaborations, and Erasmus+ exchanges.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The move follows a taskforce review and a five-day student encampment protesting the college's ties to Israel.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The university had investments in 13 Israeli companies, some linked to illegal settlements.
[src:bowdoin-college/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The decision was praised by student leaders and politicians, who called it a model for other institutions to follow.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The **20th Maine Infantry Regiment** was a volunteer regiment of the United States Army (Union Army) during the American Civil War (1861–1865), most famous for its defense of Little Round Top at the Battle of Gettysburg in Gettysburg, Pennsylvania, July 1–3, 1863.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The 133rd Engineer Battalion of the Maine Army National Guard and the United States Army today carries on the lineage and traditions of the 20th Maine.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The 20th Maine was organized in the state of Maine and mustered into federal service on August 29, 1862, with Col.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] (The regiment's undisciplined behavior while at its training camp, Camp Mason, caused Ames to exclaim, "This is a hell of a regiment!") It was assigned to the Army of the Potomac in the 3rd Brigade, 1st Division, V Corps, where it would remain until mustered out on July 16, 1865.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] At that time, the brigade also consisted of the 16th Michigan, the 12th, 17th, and 44th New York, 83rd Pennsylvania Volunteer Infantry regiments, and a Michigan company of sharpshooters.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] Prior to their notable actions at Gettysburg in July 1863, the regiment was held in reserve at Antietam in September 1862.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The regiment was also among those forced to remain overnight within sight of the Confederate lines at Fredericksburg in December 1862, forcing the regiment's Lt.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] Joshua Chamberlain to shield himself with three dead men.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The unit was unable to participate in the Battle of Chancellorsville in April–May 1863, due to a quarantine prompted by a tainted smallpox vaccine that had been issued to the unit's soldiers.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] On May 20, 1863, Colonel Ames was promoted and was succeeded as colonel and commander of the regiment by Lt.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] Chamberlain, who had been offered and declined leadership of the unit at the time it was formed.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The most notable battle was the regiment's decisive role on July 2, 1863, in the Battle of Gettysburg at Gettysburg, Pennsylvania, where it was stationed on Little Round Top hill at the extreme left of the Union line.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] When the regiment came under heavy attack from the Confederate 15th and 47th Alabama regiments (part of the division led by Maj.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The 20th Maine and the adjacent 83rd Pennsylvania together captured many men from both Alabama regiments (including Lt.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] Michael Bulger, commander of the 47th), as well as several other men of the 4th Alabama and 4th and 5th Texas regiments of the same division.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] Had the 20th Maine retreated from the hill, the entire Union line would have been flanked, endangering and hurting other Union regiments in the vicinity.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] Later actions in which the regiment participated included Second Rappahannock Station, Mine Run, The Wilderness, Spotsylvania Court House, the Siege of Petersburg, Peebles's Farm, Lewis's Farm/Quaker Road, White Oak Road, Five Forks, and Appomattox Court House, where Brevet Maj.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] Joshua Chamberlain accepted the Confederate surrender there.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The 20th Maine marched from Appomattox, Virginia, on May 2, reaching the national capital at Washington, D.C., on May 12, where the remaining original members were mustered out of service on June 4, 1865, with the remainder of the regiment leaving the federal service on July 16.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The heritage of the 20th Maine is carried on today by the 133rd Engineer Battalion, Maine Army National Guard.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The participation of the 20th Maine in the Battle of Fredericksburg is depicted in the 2003 feature film *Gods And Generals* (prequel movie to 1993's *Gettysburg* based on Michael Shaara's son Jeff Shaara's historical novel of the same name).
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The 2012 music video for the pop song "Some Nights" performed by Fun includes American Civil War Union soldiers serving in the regiment.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The regiment is victorious in a fictional battle that portrays a young Union soldier who has left his love in Maine to serve in the regiment.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] During the battle, he brutally kills a Confederate soldier in hand-to-hand combat.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The 20th Maine and its color-bearer Andrew Tozier are the subjects of "Ballad of the 20th Maine", a song by the Maine band The Ghost of Paul Revere; it is the official state ballad of Maine.
[src:bowdoin-college/20th-maine] The song "Dixieland" by Steve Earle and the Del McCoury Band is also about the 20th Maine.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The **54th Massachusetts Infantry Regiment** is an infantry regiment that saw extensive service in the Union Army during the American Civil War.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The unit was the second African-American regiment, following the 1st Kansas Colored Volunteer Infantry Regiment, organized in the Northern states during the Civil War.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Authorized by the Emancipation Proclamation, the regiment consisted of African-American enlisted men commanded by white officers.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The 54th Massachusetts was a major force in the pioneering of African-American civil war regiments, with 150 all-black regiments being raised after the raising of the 54th Massachusetts.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The unit began recruiting in February 1863 and trained at Camp Meigs on the outskirts of Boston, Massachusetts.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Prominent abolitionists were active in recruitment efforts, including Frederick Douglass, whose two sons were among the first to enlist.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Massachusetts Governor John Albion Andrew, who had long pressured the U.S.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Department of War to begin recruiting African-Americans, placed a high priority on the formation of the 54th Massachusetts.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Andrew appointed Robert Gould Shaw, the son of Boston abolitionists, to command the regiment as Colonel.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The free black community in Boston was also instrumental in recruiting efforts, utilizing networks reaching beyond Massachusetts and even into the Southern states to attract soldiers and fill out the ranks.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] After it departed from Massachusetts on May 28, 1863, the 54th Massachusetts was shipped to Beaufort, South Carolina, and became part of the X Corps commanded by Major General David Hunter.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] During its service with the X Corps, the 54th Massachusetts took part in operations against Charleston, South Carolina, including the Battle of Grimball's Landing on July 16, 1863, and the more famous Second Battle of Fort Wagner on July 18, 1863.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] During the latter engagement, the 54th Massachusetts, with other Union regiments, executed a frontal assault against Fort Wagner and suffered casualties of 20 killed, 125 wounded, and 102 missing (primarily presumed dead)—roughly 40 percent of the unit's numbers at that time.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Shaw was killed on the parapet of Fort Wagner.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] In 1864, as part of the Union Army's Department of Florida, the 54th Massachusetts took part in the Battle of Olustee.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The service of the 54th Massachusetts, particularly their charge at Fort Wagner, soon became one of the most famous episodes of the war, interpreted through artwork, poetry, and song.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] More recently, the 54th Massachusetts gained prominence in popular culture through the 1989 Oscar-winning film *Glory*.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] General recruitment of African Americans for service in the Union Army was authorized by the Emancipation Proclamation issued by President Lincoln on January 1, 1863.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Stanton accordingly instructed the Governor of Massachusetts, John A.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Andrew, to begin raising regiments including "persons of African descent" on January 26, 1863.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Andrew selected Robert Gould Shaw to be the regiment's colonel and Norwood Penrose "Pen" Hallowell to be its lieutenant colonel.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Like many officers of regiments of African-American troops, both Robert Gould Shaw and Hallowell, captains at the time, were promoted several grades.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The rest of the officers were evaluated by Shaw and Hallowell: these officers included Luis Emilio, and Garth Wilkinson "Wilkie" James, brother of Henry James and William James.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Many of these officers were of abolitionist families, and Governor Andrew himself chose several.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Norwood Hallowell was joined by his younger brother Edward Needles Hallowell, who commanded the 54th as a full colonel for the rest of the war after Shaw's death.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Twenty-four of the 29 officers was veterans, but only six had been previously commissioned.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The soldiers were recruited by black abolitionists like Frederick Douglass and Major Martin Robison Delany, M.D., and white abolitionists, including Shaw's parents.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Appleton, the first white man commissioned in the regiment, posted a notice in the *Boston Journal*.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Pierce spoke at a Joy Street Church recruiting rally, encouraging free blacks to enlist.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] About 100 people were actively involved in recruitment, including those from Joy Street Church and a group of individuals appointed by Governor Andrew to enlist black men for the 54th.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Stephens, African-American military correspondent to the *Weekly Anglo-African* who recruited over 200 men in Philadelphia and would go on to serve as a First Sergeant in the 54th.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The 54th trained at Camp Meigs in Readville near Boston.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] While there, they received considerable moral support from abolitionists in Massachusetts, including Ralph Waldo Emerson.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Material support included warm clothing items, battle flags, and $500 contributed for the equipping and training of a regimental band.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] As it became evident that many more recruits were coming forward than were needed, the medical exam for the 54th was described as "rigid and thorough" by the Massachusetts Surgeon-General.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] This resulted in what he described as "a more robust, strong and healthy set of men were never mustered into the service of the United States." Despite this, as was common in the Civil War, a few men died of disease before the 54th departed from Camp Meigs.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] By most accounts, the 54th left Boston with very high morale.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] This was despite the fact that Jefferson Davis's proclamation of December 23, 1862, effectively put both African-American enlisted men and white officers under a death sentence if captured on the grounds that they were inciting servile insurrection.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] After muster into federal service on May 13, 1863, the 54th left Boston with fanfare on May 28, and arrived to more celebrations in Beaufort, South Carolina.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] They were greeted by local blacks and by Northern abolitionists, some of whom had deployed from Boston a year earlier as missionaries to the Port Royal Experiment.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] In Beaufort, they joined with the 2nd South Carolina Volunteers, a unit of South Carolina freedmen led by James Montgomery.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] After the 2nd Volunteers' successful Raid at Combahee Ferry, Montgomery led both units in a raid on the town of Darien, Georgia.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The population had fled, and Montgomery ordered the soldiers to loot and burn the empty town.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Shaw objected to this activity and complained over Montgomery's head that burning and looting were not suitable activities for his model regiment.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The regiment's first engagement took place during the Battle of Grimball's Landing on James Island, just outside of Charleston, South Carolina, on July 16, 1863.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The Union attack on James Island was intended to draw Confederate troops away from Fort Wagner in anticipation of an upcoming Union assault on the fort.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] During the Battle of Grimball's Landing, the 54th Massachusetts stopped a Confederate advance, taking 45 casualties in the process.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] In an account of the engagement, which was later published, First Sergeant Robert John Simmons of the 54th Massachusetts (a British Army veteran from Bermuda) described a "desperate battle" in which about 250 pickets of the regiment were attacked by about 900 Confederates.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] He estimated that a reserve of 3,000 men supported the Confederates in their front.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] After the engagement, their division commander, Brig.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Terry, complimented "steadiness and soldierly conduct" of 54th Massachusetts by courier to Col.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Shaw and in his official report of the action.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] This recognition raised the morale of the regiment.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The regiment gained widespread acclaim on July 18, 1863, when it spearheaded an assault on Fort Wagner, a key position overlooking the water approach to Charleston Harbor.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The 54th Massachusetts had only recently returned from James Island after a difficult withdrawal during which they spent two days without food.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] They returned to the main Union force late on the afternoon of July 18 and the tired and hungry men were immediately placed in the vanguard of the assault force of 4,000 men.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The assault was launched at 7:45 pm along a narrow spit of land.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The distance to the Confederate line was some 1,600 yards (4,800 ft), and the spit and treacherous marshland's narrow confines disorganized the attackers.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The approach required them to pass beyond some of the Confederate fortifications before turning to make their assault.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The men crossed a water-filled ditch and took the fort's outer wall.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Because of the strength of the defending force, the position could only be held for an hour before the two Union brigades were withdrawn at around 9:00 pm.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The 54th Massachusetts numbered 600 men at the time of the assault.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Of these, 270 were killed, wounded, or captured during the engagement.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Shaw was killed, along with 29 of his men; 24 more later died of wounds, 15 were captured, 52 were missing in action and never accounted for, and 149 were wounded.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] These casualties represented the highest in the history of the regiment during a single engagement.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Two company commanders were killed during the attack.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Decades later, Sergeant William Harvey Carney was awarded the Medal of Honor for grabbing the U.S. flag as the flag bearer fell, carrying the flag to the enemy ramparts and back, and saying "Boys, the old flag never touched the ground!" which would be turned into a song in his honor in 1900.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] While other African Americans had since been granted the award by the time it was presented to Carney, Carney's is the earliest action for which the Medal of Honor was awarded to an African American.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] After the battle of Fort Wagner many officers had been killed leading to vacancies in leadership.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Non-commissioned officers exercised de-facto control of their companies due to these vacancies.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Rather than promote black soldiers to these open roles, inexperienced whites were brought from other regiments to lead the 54th Massachusetts, many of whom lacked the same anti-slavery convictions as the previous white officers.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Under the command of now-Colonel Edward Hallowell, the 54th fought a rear-guard action covering the Union retreat to Jacksonville, Florida, after their defeat at the Battle of Olustee.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] During the retreat they, along with the 35th United States Colored Troops, were able to repulse the Confederate advance and secure the Union withdrawal to Jacksonville.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The 54th Massachusetts was sent up from the reserves into the fight as the seventh New Hampshire and Eighth Colored Troops broke into retreat.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] It was here that their delaying action covered the withdrawal of the Union forces, with the 54th Massachusetts expending over 20,000 rounds of ammunition.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] After the Battle there was a large number of wounded soldiers and abandoned equipment from the 54th Massachusetts, as well as the Federal Cavalry, and part of the 7th Connecticut.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Fortunately for the Union forces, the Confederate pursuit of their massive retreat was poorly executed, and the Union soldiers were able to retreat to safety.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] While retreating, the unit was suddenly ordered to counter-march back to Ten Mile station.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The locomotive of a train carrying wounded Union soldiers had broken down, and the wounded were in danger of capture.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] When the 54th arrived, the men attached ropes to the engine and cars and manually pulled the train approximately three miles (4.8 km) to Camp Finegan, where horses were secured to help pull the train.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] After that, the train was pulled by both men and horses to Jacksonville for a total distance of ten miles (16 km).
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] It took 42 hours to pull the train that distance.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The Union army successfully retreated to Jacksonville two days after the battle on February 22.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] By the end of the ordeal, from the arrival of the 54th Massachusetts to Olustee, the fighting of the battle, and then the retreat back to Jacksonville, the troops had marched roughly 120 miles in a span of four and a half days, causing exhaustion within the regiment.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] This defeat at Olustee, along with the Union retreat after the battle, was not without consequences; there were 1,861 total casualties for the Union: 203 deaths, 1,152 wounded, and 506 missing in action.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Of that total, 87 casualties came from the 54th Massachusetts during their rearguard action with three officers and 84 enlisted men either being killed, wounded or missing.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] In contrast to the Confederate forces, this total was greatly imbalanced; with 946 casualties for the Confederates, a 5,400 strong force, roughly equal to what the Union had brought to the battle.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] In the aftermath of the war, discrepancies appeared surrounding the battle of Olustee, which revolved around the involvement of the 7th Connecticut and the 54th Massachusetts.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Brevet Major General Joseph Hawley, commanding the second brigade of Seymour's army, containing the 7th Connecticut, 7th New Hampshire and Eighth United States Colored Troops, was frustrated by what he considered inaccuracy in newspaper reports.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] He stated, "The papers are so full of lies that I know that no true history of any event was ever or ever will be written".
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Hawley wrote to Charles Dudley saying, "Don't publish the damned lie that anybody on foot but the 7th Conn. covered the entire retreat from Olustee.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The 'officer' who wrote the lie that the 54th Mass. and the 1st Nor.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] 'Saved the day' and 'covered the retreat' deserves to be shot.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Later in the Florida campaign, as part of an all-black brigade under Col.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Hartwell, the 54th Massachusetts unsuccessfully attacked entrenched Confederate militia at the November 1864 Battle of Honey Hill.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] In mid-April 1865, they fought at the Battle of Boykin's Mill, a small affair in South Carolina that proved to be one of the last engagements of the war.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The enlisted men of the 54th were recruited on the promise of pay and allowances equal to their white counterparts.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] This was supposed to amount to subsistence and $13 a month.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Instead, they were informed upon arriving in South Carolina that the Department of the South would pay them only $7 per month ($10 with $3 withheld for clothing, while white soldiers did not pay for clothing at all.) Colonel Shaw and many others immediately began protesting the measure.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Joseph Barquet, another member of the regiment, also protested the quality of the food which the soldiers were given, which led to him being court-martialed.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Although Massachusetts offered to make up the difference in pay, on principle, a regiment-wide boycott of the pay tables on paydays became the norm.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] After Shaw's death at Fort Wagner, Colonel Edward Needles Hallowell took up the fight to get full pay for the troops.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Hooper took command of the regiment starting June 18, 1864.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] After nearly a month, Colonel Hallowell returned on July 16.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Refusing their reduced pay became a point of honor for the men of the 54th.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The Congressional bill, enacted on June 16, 1864, authorized equal and full pay to those enlisted troops who had been free men as of April 19, 1861.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Of course, not all the troops qualified.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Colonel Hallowell, a Quaker, rationalized that because he did not believe in slavery, he could have all the troops swear that they were free men on April 19, 1861.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Before being given their back pay, the entire regiment was administered what became known as "the Quaker oath".
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Colonel Hallowell skillfully crafted the oath to say: "You do solemnly swear that you owed no man unrequited labor on or before the 19th day of April 1861.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Congress took action to pay the men of the 54th.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] A monument to Shaw and the 54th Massachusetts regiment, constructed 1884–1898 by Augustus Saint-Gaudens on the Boston Common, is part of the Boston Black Heritage Trail.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] In 1897, at the unveiling of the monument in Boston, William James gave a memorial address.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] A plaster of this monument was displayed in the entryway to the U.S. paintings galleries at the Paris Universal Exposition of 1900.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] A patinated plaster copy from 1900 is currently displayed in the National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Shaw and his Colored Regiment", the opening movement of *Three Places in New England*, is based both on the monument and the regiment.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Swails of the 54th Massachusetts regiment became the first African American to receive commission as an officer of a combat regiment of the regular Union army.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Colonel Shaw and his men feature prominently in Robert Lowell's Civil War centennial poem "For the Union Dead." It was originally titled "Colonel Shaw and the Massachusetts' 54th" and published in *Life Studies* (1959).
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] In the poem, Lowell uses the Robert Gould Shaw memorial as a symbolic device to comment on broader societal change, including racism and segregation, as well as his more personal struggle to cope with a rapidly changing Boston.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Blight suggested "missed filmic opportunities" that might have been included the movie.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The unit was reactivated on November 21, 2008, to serve as the Massachusetts Army National Guard ceremonial unit to render military honors at funerals and state functions.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The new unit is known as the 54th Massachusetts Volunteer Regiment.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] 54th Mass Volunteer Infantry Company A is a living history and reenactment group based in Hyde Park, Massachusetts where the original regiment was formed.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The company marches during key holidays, events and ceremonies.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] When invited, they also stage information booths, provide talks to educate the public about the 54th and participate in historical reenactments along the east coast.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] The group is affiliated with the official Massachusetts National Guard 54th regiment and often do events together.
[src:bowdoin-college/54th-massachusetts] Company A office is located at 55-59 Harvard Ave, in Hyde Park, and drill at historic Camp Meigs Playground.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Music performed **a cappella** (/ˌɑː kəˈpɛlə/ *AH kə-PEL-ə*, UK also /ˌæ kəˈpɛlə/ *AK ə-PEL-ə*; Italian: [a kkapˈpɛlla]; lit.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] 'in [the style of] the chapel'), less commonly spelled **a capella** in English, is music performed by a singer or a singing group without instrumental accompaniment.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The term *a cappella* was originally intended to differentiate between Renaissance polyphonic and Baroque *concertato* musical styles.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In the 19th century, a renewed interest in Renaissance polyphony, coupled with an ignorance of the fact that vocal parts were often doubled by instrumentalists, led to the term coming to mean unaccompanied vocal music.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The term is also used, rarely, as a synonym for *alla breve*.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Research suggests that singing and vocables may have been what early humans used to communicate before the invention of language.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The earliest instructions for performing music were found on a cuneiform tablet from around 2000 BC, while the earliest that has survived in its entirety is from the first century AD: a piece from Greece called the Seikilos epitaph.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] A cappella music was originally used in religious music, especially church music as well as anasheed and zemirot.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Gregorian chant is an example of a cappella singing, as is the majority of secular vocal music from the Renaissance.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The madrigal, up until its development in the early Baroque into an instrumentally accompanied form, was also usually performed a cappella.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Jewish and Early Christian music was largely a cappella, though instrument use subsequently increased in both religions as well as in Islam.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The early a cappella polyphonies were sometimes doubled with other instruments, which were often wind or string instruments, or organs.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] By the 16th century, a cappella polyphony had further developed, but gradually, the cantata began to take the place of a cappella forms.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Sixteenth-century a cappella polyphony, nonetheless, continued to influence church composers throughout this period and to the present day.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Recent evidence has shown that some of the early pieces by Palestrina, such as those written for the Sistine Chapel, were intended to be accompanied by an organ "doubling" for some or all of the voices.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Five of Schutz's *Historien* were Easter pieces, and of these the latter three, which dealt with the passion from three different viewpoints, those of Matthew, Luke and John, were all done a cappella style.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The parts of the crowd were sung while the solo parts which were the quoted parts from either Christ or the authors were performed in a plainchant.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In the Byzantine Rite of the Eastern Orthodox Church, Eastern Lutheran Churches and the Eastern Catholic Churches, the music performed in the liturgies is exclusively sung without instrumental accompaniment.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Early Russian *musika* which started appearing in the late 17th century, in what was known as *khorovïye kontsertï* (choral concertos) made a cappella adaptations of Venetian-styled pieces, such as the treatise, *Grammatika musikiyskaya* (1675), by Nikolai Diletsky.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Divine Liturgies and Western Rite Masses composed by famous composers such as Peter Tchaikovsky, Sergei Rachmaninoff, Alexander Arkhangelsky, and Mykola Leontovych are examples.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Instruments have divided Christendom since their introduction into worship.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] They were considered a Roman Catholic innovation, not widely practiced until the 18th century, and were opposed vigorously in worship by a number of Protestant Reformers, including Martin Luther, Ulrich Zwingli, John Calvin, and John Wesley.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Opponents of musical instruments in the Christian worship believe that such opposition is supported by the Christian scriptures and Church history.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] There is no reference to instrumental music in early church worship in the New Testament, or in the worship of churches for the first six centuries.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Several reasons have been posited throughout church history for the absence of instrumental music in church worship.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Those who do not adhere to the regulative principle of interpreting Christian scripture, believe that limiting praise to the unaccompanied chant of the early church is not commanded in scripture, and that churches in any age are free to offer their songs with or without musical instruments.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Those who subscribe to this interpretation believe that since the Christian scriptures never counter instrumental language with any negative judgment on instruments, opposition to instruments instead comes from an interpretation of history.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] There is no written opposition to musical instruments in any setting in the first century and a half of Christian churches (33–180 AD).
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The use of instruments for Christian worship during this period is also undocumented.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Toward the end of the 2nd century, Christians began condemning the instruments themselves.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Those who oppose instruments today believe these Church Fathers had a better understanding of God's desire for the church, but there are significant differences between the teachings of these Church Fathers and Christian opposition to instruments today.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Modern Christians typically believe it is acceptable to play instruments or to attend weddings, funerals, banquets, etc., where instruments are heard playing religious music.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Since "a cappella" singing brought a new polyphony (more than one note at a time) with instrumental accompaniment, it is not surprising that Protestant reformers who opposed the instruments (such as Calvin and Zwingli) also opposed the polyphony.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] While Zwingli was destroying organs in Switzerland – Luther called him a fanatic – the Church of England was burning books of polyphony.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Some Holiness Churches such as the Free Methodist Church opposed the use of musical instruments in church worship until the mid-20th century.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The Free Methodist Church allowed for local church decision on the use of either an organ or piano in the 1943 Conference before lifting the ban entirely in 1955.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The Reformed Free Methodist Church and Evangelical Wesleyan Church were formed as a result of a schism with the Free Methodist Church, with the former retaining a cappella worship and the latter retaining the rule limiting the number of instruments in the church to the piano and organ.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Certain high church services and other musical events in liturgical churches (such as the Roman Catholic Mass and the Lutheran Divine Service) may be a cappella, a practice remaining from apostolic times.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Many Mennonites also conduct some or all of their services without instruments.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Sacred Harp, a type of folk music, is an a cappella style of religious singing with shape notes, usually sung at singing conventions.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Traditional Jewish religious services did not include musical instruments given the practice of scriptural cantillation.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The use of musical instruments is traditionally forbidden on the Sabbath out of concern that players would be tempted to repair (or tune) their instruments, which is forbidden on those days.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] During the Three Weeks musical instruments are prohibited.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Many Jews consider a portion of the 49-day period of the counting of the omer between Passover and Shavuot to be a time of semi-mourning and instrumental music is not allowed during that time.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] This has led to a tradition of a cappella singing sometimes known as *sefirah* music.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The popularization of the Jewish chant may be found in the writings of the Jewish philosopher Philo, born 20 BC.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Weaving together Jewish and Greek thought, Philo promoted praise without instruments, and taught that "silent singing" (without even vocal chords) was better still.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The shofar is the only temple instrument still being used today in the synagogue, and it is only used from Rosh Chodesh Elul through the end of Yom Kippur.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The shofar is used by itself, without any vocal accompaniment, and is limited to a very strictly defined set of sounds and specific places in the synagogue service.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Peter Christian Lutkin, dean of the Northwestern University School of Music, helped popularize a cappella music in the United States by founding the Northwestern A Cappella Choir in 1906.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] An a cappella tradition was begun in 1911 by F.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Melius Christiansen, a music faculty member at St.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Olaf College Choir was established as an outgrowth of the local St.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] John's Lutheran Church, where Christiansen was organist and the choir was composed, at least partially, of students from the nearby St.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Peter, Minnesota), Augustana College (Sioux Falls, South Dakota), and Augsburg University (Minneapolis, Minnesota).
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The choirs typically range from 40 to 80 singers and are recognized for their efforts to perfect blend, intonation, phrasing and pitch in a large choral setting.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Movements in modern a cappella over the past century include barbershop and doo-wop.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Many a cappella groups can be found in high schools and colleges.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] There are amateur Barbershop Harmony Society and professional groups that sing a cappella exclusively.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Although a cappella is technically defined as singing without instrumental accompaniment, some groups use their voices to emulate instruments; others are more traditional and focus on harmonizing.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] A cappella styles range from gospel music to contemporary to barbershop quartets and choruses.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The Contemporary A Cappella Society (CASA) is a membership option for former students, whose funds support hosted competitions and events.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] A cappella music was popularized between the late 2000s and the early to mid-2010s with media hits such as the 2009–2014 TV show *The Sing-Off* and the musical comedy film series *Pitch Perfect*.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In July 1943, as a result of the American Federation of Musicians boycott of US recording studios, the a cappella vocal group *The Song Spinners* had a best-seller with "Comin' In on a Wing and a Prayer".
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In the 1950s, several recording groups, notably The Hi-Los and the Four Freshmen, introduced complex jazz harmonies to a cappella performances.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The King's Singers are credited with promoting interest in small-group a cappella performances in the 1960s.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Frank Zappa loved doo wop and a cappella, so Zappa released The Persuasions' first album from his label in 1970.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Judy Collins recorded "Amazing Grace" a cappella.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In 1983, an a cappella group known as The Flying Pickets had a Christmas 'number one' in the UK with a cover of Yazoo's (known in the US as Yaz) "Only You".
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] A cappella music attained renewed prominence from the late 1980s onward, spurred by the success of Top 40 recordings by artists such as The Manhattan Transfer, Bobby McFerrin, Huey Lewis and the News, All-4-One, The Nylons, Backstreet Boys, Boyz II Men, and *NSYNC.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Contemporary a cappella includes many vocal groups and bands who add vocal percussion or beatboxing to create a pop/rock/gospel sound, in some cases very similar to bands with instruments.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Examples of such professional groups include Straight No Chaser, Pentatonix, The House Jacks, Rockapella, Mosaic, Home Free, M-pact, and VoicePlay.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] There also remains a strong a cappella presence within Christian music, as some denominations purposefully do not use instruments during worship.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Examples of such groups are Take 6, Glad and Acappella.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Arrangements of popular music for small a cappella ensembles typically include one voice singing the lead melody, one singing a rhythmic bass line, and the remaining voices contributing chordal or polyphonic accompaniment.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] A cappella can also describe the isolated vocal track(s) from a multitrack recording that originally included instrumentation.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] These vocal tracks may be remixed or put onto vinyl records for DJs, or released to the public so that fans can remix them.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] One such example is the a cappella release of Jay-Z's *Black Album*, which Danger Mouse mixed with the Beatles' *White Album* to create *The Grey Album*.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] On their 1966 album titled *Album*, Peter, Paul and Mary included the song "Norman Normal".
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] All the sounds on that song, both vocals and instruments, were created by Paul's voice, with no actual instruments used.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In 2013, an artist by the name Smooth McGroove rose to prominence with his style of a cappella music.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] He is best known for his a cappella covers of video game music tracks on YouTube.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] in 2015, an a cappella version of Jerusalem by multi-instrumentalist Jacob Collier was selected for Beats by Dre "The Game Starts Here" for the England Rugby World Cup campaign.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] A cappella has been used as the sole orchestration for original works of musical theatre that have had commercial runs Off-Broadway (theatres in New York City with 99 to 500 seats) only four times.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The first was *Avenue X* which opened on 28 January 1994, and ran for 77 performances.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] It was produced by Playwrights Horizons with book by John Jiler, music and lyrics by Ray Leslee.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The musical style of the show's score was primarily doo-wop as the plot revolved around doo-wop group singers of the 1960s.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In 2001, The Kinsey Sicks, produced and starred in the critically acclaimed off-Broadway hit, *DRAGAPELLA!
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Starring the Kinsey Sicks* at New York's Studio 54.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] That production received a nomination for a Lucille Lortel award as Best Musical and a Drama Desk nomination for Best Lyrics.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] It was directed by Glenn Casale with original music and lyrics by Ben Schatz.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The fourth a cappella musical to appear Off-Broadway, *In Transit*, premiered October 5, 2010, and was produced by Primary Stages with book, music, and lyrics by Kristen Anderson-Lopez, James-Allen Ford, Russ Kaplan, and Sara Wordsworth.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Set primarily in the New York City subway system its score features an eclectic mix of musical genres (including jazz, hip hop, Latin, rock, and country).
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In Transit incorporates vocal beat boxing into its contemporary a cappella arrangements through the use of a subway beat boxer character.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Beat boxer and actor Chesney Snow performed this role for the 2010 Primary Stages production.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] According to the show's website, it is scheduled to reopen for an open-ended commercial run in the Fall of 2011.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In 2011, the production received four Lucille Lortel Award nominations including Outstanding Musical, Outer Critics Circle and Drama League nominations, as well as five Drama Desk nominations including Outstanding Musical and won for Outstanding Ensemble Performance.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In December 2016, *In Transit* became the first a cappella musical on Broadway.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Barbershop music is one of several uniquely American art forms that involve cappella music as well as African American singers.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The earliest documented quartets all began in barber shops.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In 1938, the first formal men's barbershop organization was formed, known as the Society for the Preservation and Encouragement of Barber Shop Quartet Singing in America (S.P.E.B.S.Q.S.A), and in 2004 rebranded itself and officially changed its public name to the Barbershop Harmony Society (BHS).
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Today, BHS has about 22,000 members in approximately 800 chapters across the United States and Canada, and the barbershop style has spread around the world with organizations in many other countries.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The Barbershop Harmony Society provides a highly organized competition structure for a cappella quartets and choruses singing in the barbershop style.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In 1945, the first formal women's barbershop organization, Sweet Adelines, was formed.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In 1953, Sweet Adelines became an international organization, although it did not change its name to Sweet Adelines International until 1991 and subsequently changed its name to SingUnited International in 2026.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The membership of nearly 25,000 women, all singing in English, includes choruses in most of the fifty United States as well as in Australia, Canada, Finland, Germany, Ireland, Japan, New Zealand, Spain, Sweden, the United Kingdom, and the Netherlands.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Headquartered in Tulsa, Oklahoma, the organization encompasses more than 1,200 registered quartets and 600 choruses.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In 1959, a second women's barbershop organization started.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Based on democratic principles which continue to this day, Harmony, Incorporated is smaller than its counterpart, but has an atmosphere of friendship and competition.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] With over 2,000 members in the United States and Canada, Harmony, Inc. uses the same rules in contest that the Barbershop Harmony Society uses.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] High school groups may have conductors or student leaders who keep the tempo for the group, or beatboxers/vocal percussionists.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Since 2013, summer training programs have appeared, such as A Cappella Academy in Los Angeles, California (founded by Ben Bram, Rob Dietz, and Avi Kaplan) and Camp A Cappella in Dayton, Ohio (founded by Deke Sharon and Brody McDonald).
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] These programs teach about different aspects of a cappella music, including vocal performance, arranging, and beatboxing/vocal percussion.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The Rensselyrics of Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute (formerly known as the RPI Glee Club), established in 1873 is perhaps the oldest known collegiate a cappella group.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The longest continuously singing group is likely The Whiffenpoofs of Yale University, which formed in 1909 and once included Cole Porter as a member.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Collegiate a cappella groups grew throughout the 20th century.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] All-women a cappella groups followed shortly, with names frequently parodying men's groups: the Smiffenpoofs of Smith College (1936), the Night Owls of Vassar College (1942), The Shwiffs of Connecticut College (1944), and The Chattertocks of Brown University (1951).
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] A cappella groups exploded in popularity beginning in the 1990s, fueled in part by a change in style popularized by the Tufts University Beelzebubs and the Boston University Dear Abbeys.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The new style used voices to emulate modern rock instruments, including vocal percussion/"beatboxing".
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Some larger universities now have multiple groups.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In December 2009, a new television competition series called *The Sing-Off* aired on NBC.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The show featured eight a cappella groups from the United States and Puerto Rico vying for the prize of $100,000 and a recording contract with Epic Records/Sony Music.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The show was judged by Ben Folds, Shawn Stockman, and Nicole Scherzinger and was won by an all-male group from Puerto Rico called Nota.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The show returned for a second, third, fourth, and fifth season, won by Committed, Pentatonix, Home Free, and The Melodores from Vanderbilt University respectively.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Each year, hundreds of collegiate a cappella groups submit their strongest songs in a competition to be on The Best of College A Cappella (BOCA), an album compilation of tracks from the best college a cappella groups around the world.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The album is produced by Varsity Vocals ,which also produces the International Championship of Collegiate A Cappella , and Deke Sharon.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Collegiate a cappella groups also submit their tracks to Voices Only, a two-disc series released annually since 2005.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] From 2014 to 2019, the Women's A Cappella Association (WACA) produced an annual best of women's a cappella album.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The popularity of a cappella was revived by television shows and movies such as *Glee* and *Pitch Perfect,* with the latter being more a cappella-focused than the former, whose focus lies more on traditional musical theater.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Since the release of Pitch Perfect in late 2012, the amount of coed a cappella groups has risen far more sharply than in the years prior.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan has no official anthem because of views by the Taliban of music as un-Islamic.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] However, the *de facto* national anthem of Afghanistan is an a cappella nasheed, as musical instruments are virtually banned as corrupting and un-Islamic.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Australia saw a rise in a cappella groups during the 1980s and 1990s with groups such as Blindman’s Holiday, Arramaeida, Martenitsa Choir, Cafe at the Gate of Salvation, and the Heavenly Light Quartet.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Vocal music and community choirs have become popular in most towns and suburbs of Australia since 2010, with regular concerts, events and festivals dedicated solely to vocal music performances.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The first a cappella group in Iran is the Damour Vocal Band, which was able to perform on national television despite a ban on women singing.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The musical show *Strepsils Stereo* is credited for introducing the art of a cappella in Pakistan.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Composer Dinesh Subasinghe became the first Sri Lankan to write a cappella pieces for SATB choirs.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] He wrote "The Princes of the Lost Tribe" and "Ancient Queen of Somawathee" for Menaka De Sahabandu and Bridget Helpe's choirs, respectively, based on historical incidents in ancient Sri Lanka.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Voice Print is also a professional a cappella music group in Sri Lanka.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The European a cappella tradition is strong in the countries around the Baltic, including in Sweden as described by Richard Sparks in *The Swedish Choral Miracle* in 2000.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Swedish a cappella choirs have over the last 25 years won around 25% of the annual prestigious European Grand Prix for Choral Singing (EGP) that despite its name is open to choirs from all over the world (see list of laureates in the Wikipedia article on the EGP competition).
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Sparks explains that in Sweden an unusually large proportion of the populations (5% is often cited) regularly sing in choirs.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In British universities, there are numerous a capella groups.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] UK a capella organisations include The Voice Festival UK and the integration of the United Kingdom into the International Championship of Collegiate A Cappella.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] South Asian a cappella features a fusion of music from the Indian subcontinent, which places it in the category of South Asian fusion music.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] A cappella is gaining popularity among South Asians with the emergence of primarily Hindi-English college groups.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The first South Asian a cappella group was Penn Masala, an all-male group founded in 1996 at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The first co-ed South Asian a cappella was Anokha, from the University of Maryland, formed in 2001.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The first South Asian A Cappella competition was "Anahat," hosted by the Indus student organization at UC Berkeley.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Maize Mirchi, the co-ed a cappella group from the University of Michigan became the first South Asian group to advance to ICCA finals in 2023.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The South Asian a cappella competitive circuit is governed by the Association of South-Asian A Cappella (ASA), a non-profit organization formed in 2016.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The competitive circuit consists of qualifier "bid" competitions all over the United States, as well as the national championship, All-American Awaaz.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The first winner of the championship title was Swaram A Cappella at Texas A&M University, who won 1st place at All-American Awaaz in 2017 in New York City as well as in 2018 in Chicago.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Dhamakapella currently holds the record for most All-American Awaaz championships, winning three consecutive championships in 2022, 2023, and 2024.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In addition to singing words, some a cappella singers also emulate instrumentation by reproducing instrumental sounds with their vocal cords and mouth, often pitched using specialised pitch pipes.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] One of the earliest 20th century practitioners of this method were The Mills Brothers.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] More recently, "Twilight Zone" by 2 Unlimited was sung a cappella to the instrumentation on the comedy television series *Tompkins Square*.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Another famous example of emulating instrumentation instead of singing the words is the theme song for *The New Addams Family* series on Fox Family Channel (now Freeform).
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Groups such as Vocal Sampling emulate Latin rhythms a cappella.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] In the 1960s, the Swingle Singers used their voices to emulate musical instruments to Baroque and Classical music.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Vocal artist Bobby McFerrin is famous for his instrumental emulation.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] A cappella group Naturally Seven recreates entire songs using vocal tones for every instrument.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] Beatboxing, more accurately known as vocal percussion, is a technique used in a cappella music popularized by the hip-hop community, where rap is often performed a cappella.
[src:bowdoin-college/a-cappella] The advent of vocal percussion has become prevalent in modern arrangements.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] The college has its origin as a theological institute founded by Wesleyan Methodists at Leoni, Michigan, in 1845.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] This institution merged with Leoni Seminary, another Methodist school, in 1855 to form **Michigan Union College**.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] In 1859, that institution closed and its assets were transferred to Adrian "through the efforts of the antislavery leader and educator, Rev.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Asa Mahan, who was elected first president of the new Adrian College".
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] The college was chartered by the Michigan Legislature on March 28, 1859.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] In the early stages of the Civil War the college volunteered itself as a base for the formation of Michigan regiments for the Union side.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] The current Valade Hall building sits on the site of the former base camp for these soldiers.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] A marker designating the college as a Michigan Historic Site was erected by the Michigan Historical Commission.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] An additional marker commemorating Camp Williams and the Fourth Michigan Volunteer Infantry as a Michigan Historic Site was erected by the Michigan Historical Commission.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] The original campus was built in the mid-19th century.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] It would be almost a century later that President John Dawson began a major construction phase of the campus, including most of the residence halls, academic buildings, a student union, and the administration building.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] More recently, current President Jeff Docking has introduced many plans to revitalize Adrian College and its campus, including the construction of new buildings, renovation of old ones, and programs related to athletics.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] The college is making renovations and expansions to the Science, Business, Visual Arts, and Performing Arts departments.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Adrian College offers over 90 majors and pre-professional programs.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] It also offers six graduate programs using a unique 4+1 structure for current students.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Graduate programs exist in: Accounting, Athletic Training, Criminal Justice, Industrial Chemistry, Teacher Education, and Sports Administration and Leadership.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Over the past several years eight of the nine academic buildings were renovated, and fundraising is currently being undertaken on the final building, Mahan Hall for Art and Interior Design.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Institutes are thematic centers focusing on areas of interest supporting the mission of Adrian College.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] As of 2015, there are eight institutes including Career Planning, Creativity, Entrepreneurial Studies, Ethics, Health Studies, Romney Institute for Law and Public Policy, Study Abroad, Sports Medicine, and Teacher Education.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Each institute provides programming to students, faculty, staff, and wider community.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Adrian College athletic teams, nicknamed the "Bulldogs", are part of the Michigan Intercollegiate Athletic Association and the National Collegiate Athletic Association Division III.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] The men's NCAA Division III hockey team is a member of the Northern Collegiate Hockey Association.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] The men's volleyball team joined the Midwest Collegiate Volleyball League.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Adrian College is the third college or university to offer women's hockey as a varsity sport in Michigan.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] In 2011, the college reached an agreement with the federal Department of Education's Office of Civil Rights, resolving complaints that the college had violated Title IX.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] The college was found guilty of eleven violations of the law that governs gender equality, and agreed to make several changes to its athletic programs.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Adrian expanded its athletic programs in the 2007–2008 academic year to add NCAA Division III men's and women's ice hockey and men's Division I ACHA hockey along with synchronized skating and NCAA Division III men's and women's lacrosse.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] The Bulldog's lacrosse program is the first varsity program in MI since the induction of Title IX.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Women's bowling was added for the 2008-2009 year.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Later, it added men's and women's rowing in 2018.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] College football has been a part of the history of Adrian college since 1892, when Hillsdale College defeated Adrian by a score of 56–0.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] The first head football coach on record was E.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Since then, the program has won 16 conference championships, the first in 1911 and the most recent in 2012 and 2014.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] The head coach is Joe Palka who took over in 2024.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] The team finished 26-3 and did not make the NCAA Division III Tournament.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] They would qualify for the NCAA National Tournament nine times before winning their first NCAA Div.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] III National Championship on March 26, 2022, in Lake Placid, New York.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Men's and women's rowing were added in 2017.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] In 2018, Adrian College's rowing programs joined the Mid-Atlantic Rowing Conference (MARC).
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] In 2018, the program welcomed an inaugural freshman class of 25 rowers.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Intramurals are part of Adrian College and the athletic department.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Some of the intramural teams include Flag Football, 5-on-5 Basketball, Coed Volleyball League, Broomball, 7-on-7 Soccer, and 3-on-3 Basketball.
[src:bowdoin-college/adrian-college] Greek life on campus includes several fraternities and sororities.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The college was founded in 1889 as **Decatur Female Seminary** by Presbyterian minister Frank Henry Gaines.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] In 1890, the name was changed to **Agnes Scott Institute** to honor the mother of the college's primary benefactor, Col.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The name was changed again to Agnes Scott College in 1906 and remains today a women's college.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott is considered the first higher education institution in the state of Georgia to receive regional accreditation.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The ninth and current president since July 2018 is Leocadia I.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Zak, who previously worked as director of the U.S.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] On July 27, 1994, the campus was listed on the National Register of Historic Places as part of the *South Candler Street-Agnes Scott College Historic District*.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The historic district boundaries are East College Ave., South McDonough St., S.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Candler St., East Hill St. and East Davis St.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] It includes the entire campus, as well as historic homes adjacent to the campus.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The campus is also designated by the City of Decatur as a historic district.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The Reverend Frank Henry Gaines served as the first President of Agnes Scott, formally known as Decatur Female Seminary School, for 27 years (1896–1923).
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] During his 27-year presidency, he ensured stability and success for the school, including the transition to the collegiate level, accreditation by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools, acquisition of 20 acres of land and 21 buildings and an increase in assets from $5,000 to $1.5 million.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott College is located within walking distance of downtown Decatur.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] It is served by Decatur station on the MARTA rail system, which is also a hub for buses, allowing students to travel to the greater Atlanta area.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott occupies more than 90 acres (360,000 m2) in Decatur.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The college also owns the Avery Glen apartments as well as more than a dozen houses in the surrounding neighborhoods housing faculty, staff, and students.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] There are also six dedicated undergraduate dormitories located on campus.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] American poet Robert Frost was first invited to speak at Agnes Scott in 1935, by English professor Emma May Laney, and he visited the college every winter from 1945 until his death in 1963.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] During his visits, he would read poetry in Presser Hall.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] A statue of the poet sculpted by George W.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] A collection of Robert Frost's poetry and letters can be viewed on the second floor of the McCain Library.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott (Main) Hall, named after Agnes Irvine Scott, is located at the center of "the main loop" and is a one among many Agnes Scott buildings that was listed in the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Main was built in 1891, making it the oldest building on campus.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] This is documented in the history of Agnes Scott by McNair titled *Lest We Forget* published in 1983.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] As technology became more advanced so did Main.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Main Hall was the first building on campus and in the neighborhood to have electric lighting.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Some say that people would gather outside of Main at night just to admire the light shining within the building.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1891, the Gazebo at Agnes Scott college has served a multitude of purposes throughout the years.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] It was originally located in front of Agnes Scott (Main) Hall, however in 1926 it was moved to the west end of Rebekah Scott Hall.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The gazebo has been used as an office, meeting room, meditation chapel, and the Day Student Hut.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1906, Rebekah Scott Hall is the second oldest building remaining at Agnes Scott College.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Rebekah Scott Hall cost $70,000 to build.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] It is named after George Washington Scott's wife, Rebekah Butcher Scott.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The first floor of Rebekah Scott Hall contains offices, the office of financial aid, and the office of admissions.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The second and third floors are used as student housing.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Inman Hall, known commonly as Inman Hall, was built in 1911 and is the oldest building at Agnes Scott College which is used exclusively for student housing.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] In 1985, Inman had major renovations and the third floor was converted into study spaces for students.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] It is made from Indiana limestone and is three stories high.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The building faces west and has a large veranda which stretches along the front of the building.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Jennie D, Inman Hall was gifted to Agnes Scott College by Samuel.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1923, the Anna Young Alumnae House is dedicated to former science professor and Agnes Scott alumnae, Anna Irwin Young.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Originally the Alumnae House was a central gathering place for ASC alumnae.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The house and bedrooms are now used as a campus guest house.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Behind the house is the Alumnae Garden which houses a statue honoring Robert Frost.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The Anna Young Alumnae House underwent renovations from 2005 until 2009, after which it was re-opened.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The Bradley Observatory at Agnes Scott houses the Beck Telescope, a 30-inch (760 mm) Cassegrain reflector, as well as a planetarium with 70-seat capacity and a radio telescope.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Recently Agnes Scott College and the Georgia Tech Research Institute have collaborated on a project that added a LIDAR facility to the observatory.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The college's science building, the Bullock Science Center, contains a three-story rendering of part of the nucleotide sequence from Agnes Scott's mitochondrial DNA.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The DNA came from a blood sample of an ASC alumna who is a direct descendant of the college's namesake.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott has committed to becoming a carbon-neutral institute by the college's 150th anniversary in 2039 and has taken steps such as partnering with the Clean Air Campaign to reduce its impact on the local environment.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] As of 2015, the college has five solar arrays, four of which are part of Georgia Power's Advanced Solar Initiative.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The fifth array is on the rooftop of the Bradley Observatory and is also used for student research.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The renovation of Campbell Hall into a mixed-use residence hall, learning center, and office space was concluded in 2014 and included installation of a hydro-geothermic HVAC system.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott offers 34 undergraduate majors and 9 graduate and post-baccalaureate programs.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The undergraduate core curriculum SUMMIT focuses on leadership development, global learning, and digital literacy.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] In 2019, Agnes Scott received the Heiskell Award for Scholars as Drivers of Innovation for its SUMMIT curriculum.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Undergraduate students are able to cross-register in other ARCHE member institutions.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The library at Agnes Scott College was an original Carnegie library built in 1910.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] A new library was authorized by the board of trustees in 1935 and opened in the fall of 1936.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] This new library was called the "Carnegie Library" and the original library was turned into a student center.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] It was renamed in 1951 for James McCain, on the occasion of his retirement as the 2nd President of the college.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] As of fall 2025, the student body consists of over 900 undergraduate and graduate students.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Approximately 60% of undergraduates that year were from Georgia.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Given Agnes Scott's emphasis on "mak[ing] lifelong friends, shar[ing] unforgettable experiences, discover[ing] meaningful places and find[ing] belonging in [their] community," a majority of students are encouraged to live on campus.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Thus, most students are expected to live in on-campus housing for all four years as an undergraduate at Agnes Scott College.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] However, the proportion of commuter students has increased (from 15.6 to 18.0 percent between the 2014–2015 and 2019–2020 academic year) due to limited housing caused from an increase in the student population (from 849 to 986 total students) and renovations to the residence halls.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] There are six resident halls situated around the Northern edge of the campus: Winship, Walters, Inman, Rebekah, Campbell, and Agnes Scott Hall (nicknamed "Main").
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] There are over 60 student organizations on campus.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The college hosts several student publications, including *The Silhouette*, the college's yearbook published annually, and *The Aurora*, Agnes Scott's literary magazine, and *The Profile*, Agnes Scott newspaper.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] All students are invited to join the staff.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott is a member of the National Collegiate Athletic Association Division III which fields six sports teams including basketball, cross country, soccer, softball, tennis, and volleyball.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] All teams compete in the Collegiate Conference of the South (CCS).
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott was named as one of the Colleges That Change Lives (CTCL).
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The campus has been a filming location for many productions, including the filming location for Windsor College in Scream 2, with its campus standing in for the fictional university where Sidney Prescott enrolls to escape her past.
[src:bowdoin-college/agnes-scott-college] The college's Gothic architecture, particularly the main hall, provided the backdrop for many scenes, including the gazebo where a key reunion takes place.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] On March 23, 1835, Methodist settlers in Spring Arbor Township obtained a charter for a new seminary from the Michigan Territorial Legislature.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Construction began in 1837 outside Spring Arbor but the Panic of 1837 ended the project.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] A petition to move the seminary to Albion was approved by the legislature in 1839.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Sixty acres (243,000 m2) of land were donated by Jesse Crowell to the renamed "Wesleyan Seminary", and construction began in 1841.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] The first classes were held in 1843 in the local Methodist Church.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] In 1844, classes began in the newly constructed Central Building, rebuilt as the present Robinson Hall in 1907.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] The "Albion Female Collegiate Institute", founded in 1850, merged in 1857 under the name "The Wesleyan Seminary and Female College at Albion"; the merger was finalized in 1861, under the name "Albion College".
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] The legislature authorized the college to confer full four-year college degrees upon both men and women that same year.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Albion offers bachelor's degrees in business, the humanities, fine arts, natural sciences, and social sciences.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] It provides study-abroad programs in Europe, Latin America, Israel, Africa, Asia, and Australia.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Albion is perhaps best known for its equestrian center, the Nancy G.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Held Equestrian Center, and its biology and physical education programs.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] The three popular first majors, by number of 2021 graduates, were Biology/Biological Sciences (43), Economics (33), and Communication (28).
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] The 144-acre (0.58 km2) Whitehouse Nature Center at Albion works with public schools and the community.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] It features six miles of trails, 400 plant species, almost 170 bird species, 25 acres of oak-hickory and flood-plain forest, a tall-grass prairie and spring in the Adele D.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Whitehouse Wildflower Garden, an arboretum of Michigan trees and shrubs, 34 acres of farmland and research projects, and an interpretative building.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Albion College Astronomical Observatory was built in 1883-84 with encouragement from Samuel Dickie, later the college president.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Since 1990 one student went on to be a Rhodes Scholar, three were Goldwater Scholars, four Truman Scholars and seventeen Fulbright Scholars.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Albion College is home to the Prentiss M.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Brown Honors Center & Astronomical Observatory, named after Prentiss M.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Representative who graduated from Albion College in 1911.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] The observatory is recognized as a Michigan State Historical Site and is used for both educational purposes and public viewing events, allowing students and community members to observe celestial objects such as planets, stars, and solar events.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] One of the notable features of the observatory is the 8.25" Alvan Clark Telescope, which dates back to the late 19th century.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Alvan Clark & Sons were renowned telescope makers and the presence of this telescope adds historical and educational value to the observatory.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] According to "Old Albion", a college history published in 1909, Alvan Clark himself crafted the Albion telescope, marking it as the last telescope he made before his death.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Although this claim remains unverified, Clark's health was declining in the early 1880s and the extent of his work in the years leading up to his death in 1887 is not well-documented.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] As of 2021 Fall enrollment, the student body was 53% female and 47% male.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] 73% of students were Michigan residents, 26% from out-of-state, and 1% from foreign countries.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Ninety-eight percent of students are enrolled full-time.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Prior to the 2010s the enrollment was heavily white and non-low income.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] The numbers of black and Hispanic students increased, along with those of first-time university students and lower income students, due to a drive to increase and diversify enrollment.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Between 2013 and 2020, Albion increased its minority enrollment from 18% to 41%, and 48% of the incoming class in 2020 identified as persons of color.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] The total cost of attending Albion full time as of 2022 was $67,310.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Albion offers financial aid of some form to 100% of its students.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] The average financial aid package as of December 2022 was $53,714 per student.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Albion College is home to six social fraternities and as many sororities.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] All are members of the North American Interfraternity Conference and all comprise Albion College's InterFraternity Council (IFC).
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] The song "Sweetheart of Sigma Chi" was written in 1911 by Byron D.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Dudleigh Vernor (Albion, 1914), and first performed by Harry Clifford (Albion, 1911) while undergraduates at Albion College.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Albion College is also home to fifteen honorary, professional, service, and special interest fraternities, including Phi Beta Kappa, established as the Michigan Beta chapter in 1940.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Albion athletics teams are nicknamed the *Britons*.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] The college is a member of the Michigan Intercollegiate Athletic Association (MIAA).
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Albion has overall won 173 men's MIAA titles (tied for 2nd overall), as well as 26 women's MIAA titles (5th overall).
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] Albion football won the NCAA Division III national championship in 1994.
[src:bowdoin-college/albion-college] The esports team started in the 2021-2022 academic year.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In addition to its Brunswick campus, Bowdoin owns a 118-acre (48 ha) coastal studies center on Orr's Island and a 200-acre (81 ha) scientific field station on Kent Island in the Bay of Fundy.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The college was a founding member of its athletic conference, the New England Small College Athletic Conference, and the Colby-Bates-Bowdoin Consortium, an athletic conference and inter-library exchange with Bates College and Colby College.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin has over 30 varsity teams, and the school mascot was selected as a polar bear in 1913 to honor Robert Peary, a Bowdoin alumnus who claimed to have led the first successful expedition to the North Pole.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin College was chartered in 1794 by the Massachusetts State Legislature and was later redirected under the jurisdiction of the Maine Legislature.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] It was named for former Massachusetts governor James Bowdoin, whose son James Bowdoin III was an early benefactor.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin began to develop in the 1820s, a decade in which Maine became an independent state as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] President Franklin Pierce and two literary figures, Nathaniel Hawthorne and Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, both of whom graduated Phi Beta Kappa in 1825.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Pierce and Hawthorne began an official militia company called the 'Bowdoin Cadets'.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The Phi Beta Kappa Society was active at Bowdoin before the Civil War and featured anti-slavery speakers.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] From its founding, Bowdoin was known to educate the sons of the political elite and "catered very largely to the wealthy conservative from the state of Maine".
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] During the first half of the 19th century, Bowdoin required of its students a certificate of "good moral character" as well as knowledge of Latin and Ancient Greek, geography, algebra, and the major works of Cicero, Xenophon, Virgil and Homer.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Harriet Beecher Stowe started writing her influential anti-slavery novel, *Uncle Tom's Cabin*, in Brunswick while her husband was teaching at the college.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Brigadier General (and Brevet Major General) Joshua Chamberlain, a Bowdoin alumnus and professor, was present at the surrender of the Army of Northern Virginia at Appomattox Court House in 1865.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Chamberlain, a Medal of Honor recipient who later served as governor of Maine and president of Bowdoin, fought at Gettysburg, where he commanded the 20th Maine in defense of Little Round Top.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Other notable Civil War-era alumni include Major General Oliver Otis Howard, class of 1850, who led the Freedmen's Bureau and later founded Howard University; Massachusetts Governor John Andrew, class of 1837, who was responsible for forming the 54th Massachusetts; and William P.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Fessenden (1823) and Hugh McCulloch (1827), both of whom served as Secretary of the Treasury during the Lincoln Administration.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] With strained relations over slavery between political parties, President Franklin Pierce appointed Jefferson Davis as his Secretary of War, and the college awarded the future President of the Confederacy an honorary degree.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The Jefferson Davis Award was established in 1972 following a donation from the United Daughters of the Confederacy and was given to students excelling in legal studies.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The award was discontinued in 2015, with the college president citing it as inappropriate because it honored someone "whose mission was to preserve and institutionalize slavery".
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Although Bowdoin's Medical School of Maine closed in 1921, it produced notable graduates including Augustus Stinchfield, who received his M.D. in 1868 and became one of the co-founders of the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minnesota.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In 1877, the college graduated Charles Morse, the American banker who established a near-monopoly of the ice business in New York, which contributed to the financial Panic of 1907.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The college educated and graduated Arctic explorers Robert E.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Peary named Bowdoin Fjord and Bowdoin Glacier after his alma mater.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Peary led what he claimed was the first successful expedition to reach the North Pole in April 1909, and MacMillan, a member of Peary's crew, explored Greenland, Baffin Island, and Labrador in the schooner *Bowdoin* between 1908 and 1954.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] White, Jr., class of 1899, served as Senate Minority Leader from 1944 to 1947 and Senate Majority Leader from 1947 to 1949.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Mitchell, class of 1954, served as Senate Majority Leader from 1989 to 1995 before assuming an active role in the Northern Ireland peace process.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In 1970, the college became one of a very limited number of liberal arts colleges to make the SAT optional in the admissions process.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In 1971, after nearly 180 years as a men's college, Bowdoin admitted its first class of women.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Also in 1971, Bowdoin became a founding member of the New England Small College Athletic Conference (NESCAC) and began competing in the Colby-Bates-Bowdoin Consortium with Bates College and Colby College.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The consortium became both an athletic rivalry and an academic exchange program.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] On February 28, 1997, Bowdoin's Board of Trustees approved a plan to phase out fraternities on campus, replacing them with a system of college-owned social houses.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] On January 18, 2008, Bowdoin announced that it would eliminate loans for all students receiving financial aid, replacing those loans with grants beginning with the 2008–2009 academic year.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] President Barry Mills stated, "Some see a calling in such vital but often low-paying fields such as teaching or social work.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] With significant debt at graduation, some students will undoubtedly be forced to make career or education choices not based on their talents, interests, and promise in a particular field but rather on their capacity to repay student loans.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In February 2009, following a $10 million donation by Subway co-founder and alumnus Peter Buck, class of 1952, the college completed a $250 million capital campaign.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The college also completed major construction projects on campus, including a renovation of the art museum and a new fitness center named after Peter Buck.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] On July 1, 2015, Clayton Rose succeeded Mills as president.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Eight years later, on July 1, 2023, Safa Zaki succeeded Rose as the first woman to serve as president of the college.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In February 2025, students occupied the Smith Union building to demand that the university divest from arms manufacturers, marking the first pro-Palestinian encampment during the second Trump administration.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The encampment followed Trump's comments on occupying Gaza and perceived inaction following an Israel divestment referendum passed by the student body a year prior.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The acceptance rate for the class of 2030 was 6.5%.The college received more than 14,727 applications for the class of 2030 – the highest application number in the college's history and a continuation of the rise in applications over the past four years.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Applications increased by about 50%, since the class of 2024 and about 100% since the class of 2021.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The April 17, 2008, edition of *The Economist* noted Bowdoin in an article on university admissions: "So-called 'almost-Ivies' such as Bowdoin and Middlebury also saw record low admission rates this year (18% each).
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] It is now as hard to get into Bowdoin, says the college's admissions director, as it was to get into Princeton in the 1970s." Many students apply for financial aid, and around 85% of those who apply to receive aid.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin is a need-blind and no-loans institution.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] While a significant portion of the student body hails from New England—including nearly 25% from Massachusetts and 10% from Maine—recent classes have drawn from an increasingly national and international pool.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The median family income of Bowdoin students is $195,900, with 57% of students coming from the top 10% of highest-earning families and 17.5% from the bottom 60%.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Although Bowdoin once had a reputation for homogeneity (both ethnically and socioeconomically), a diversity campaign has increased the percentage of students of color in recent classes to more than 31%.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In fact, admission of minorities goes back at least as far as John Brown Russwurm 1826, Bowdoin's first Black college graduate and the third Black graduate of any American college.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Course distribution requirements were abolished in the 1970s but were reinstated by a faculty majority vote in 1981 due to an initiative by oral communication and film professor Barbara Kaster.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] She insisted that distribution requirements would ensure students a more well-rounded education in a diversity of fields and therefore present them with more career possibilities.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The requirements of at least two courses in each of the categories of Natural Sciences/mathematics, social and behavioral sciences, humanities/Fine Arts, and foreign studies (including languages) took effect for the class of 1987 and have been gradually amended since then.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Current requirements require one course each in natural sciences, quantitative reasoning, visual and performing arts, international perspectives, and difference, power, and inequity.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] A small writing-intensive course, called a first-year seminar, is also required.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In 1990, the Bowdoin faculty voted to change the four-level grading system to the traditional A, B, C, D, and F system.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The previous system, consisting of high honors, honors, pass, and fail, was devised primarily to de-emphasize the importance of grades and to reduce competition.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In 2002, the faculty decided to change the grading system to incorporate plus and minus grades.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In 2006, Bowdoin was named a "Top Producer of Fulbright Awards for American Students" by the Institute of International Education.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Other notable Bowdoin faculty include (or have included): Edville Gerhardt Abbott, Charles Beitz, John Bisbee, Paul Chadbourne, Thomas Cornell, Kristen R.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Johnson, Richard Morgan, Elliott Schwartz, Kenneth Chenault, and Scott Sehon.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] News & World Report* rankings, Bowdoin was ranked tied at 5th best overall among liberal arts colleges in the United States, tied at 6th for "Best Undergraduate Teaching", 7th in "Best Value Schools", and tied at 30th for "Most Innovative Schools".
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In the 2022 *Forbes* college rankings, Bowdoin was ranked 48th overall among 498 universities, liberal arts colleges, and service academies and 7th among private liberal arts colleges.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin College is accredited by the New England Commission of Higher Education.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin was ranked first among 1,204 small colleges in the U.S. by Niche in 2017, but has since fallen to 6th.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Based on students' SAT scores, Bowdoin is tied with Williams for 5th in Business Insider's smartest liberal arts colleges, with an average score of 1435 for math and critical reading combined.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Among all colleges, it is tied with Brown, Carnegie Mellon, and Williams for 22nd.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The college was ranked 5th in the country by *Washington Monthly* in 2019 based on its contribution to the public good, as measured by social mobility, research, and promoting public service.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In 2006, *Newsweek* described Bowdoin as a "New Ivy", one of a number of liberal arts colleges and universities outside of the Ivy League, and it has also been dubbed a "Hidden Ivy".
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin's dining services have been ranked No.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin uses food from its organic garden in its two major dining halls, and every academic year begins with a lobster bake outside Farley Fieldhouse.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Recalling his days at Bowdoin in a 2005 interview, Professor Richard E.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Morgan (class of 1959) described student life at the then-all-male school as "monastic" and noted that "the only things to do were either work or drink".
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] This is corroborated by the *Official Preppy Handbook,* which in 1980 ranked Bowdoin the number two drinking school in the country, behind Dartmouth.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Since abolishing Greek fraternities in the late 1990s, Bowdoin has switched to a system in which entering students are assigned a "college house" affiliation correlating with their first-year dormitory.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] While six houses were originally established following the construction of two new dorms, two were added effective in the fall of 2007, and one added in the fall of 2019, bringing the current total to eight: Baxter, Quinby, MacMillan, Howell, Helmreich, Reed, Burnett, and Boody-Johnson.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The college houses are physical buildings around campus that host parties and other events throughout the year.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Those students who choose not to live in their affiliated house retain their affiliation and are considered members throughout their Bowdoin career.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The largest student group on campus is the Outing Club, which leads canoeing, kayaking, rafting, camping, and backpacking trips throughout Maine.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] One of the school's two historic rival literary societies, The Peucinian Society, has recently been revitalized from its previous form.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The Peucinian Society was founded in 1805.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] This organization counts such people as Henry Wadsworth Longfellow and Joshua Lawrence Chamberlain among its former members.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The other, the now-defunct Athenian Society, included Nathaniel Hawthorne and Franklin Pierce as members.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin competes in the Standard Platform League of RoboCup as the Northern Bites, where teams compete with five autonomous Aldebaran Nao robots.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin won the world championship in RoboCup 2007, beating Carnegie Mellon University, and finished 2nd in the 2015 US Open.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin's student newspaper, *The Bowdoin Orient*, is the oldest continuously published college weekly in the United States.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The Orient was named the second-best tabloid-sized college weekly at a Collegiate Associated Press conference in March 2007 and the best college newspaper in New England by the New England Society of News Editors in 2018.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The school's literary magazine, *The Quill*, was published between 1897 and 2015.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] *The Bowdoin Globalist*, an international news, culture, and politics magazine affiliated with the Global21 organization of college magazines, has been publishing since 2012.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] *The Bowdoin Globalist* transitioned to a digital-only platform in 2015 and changed its name to *The Bowdoin Review*.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The college's radio station, WBOR, has been operating since the early 1940s.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In 1999, *The Bowdoin Cable Network* was formed, producing a weekly newscast and several student-created shows per semester.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Six *a cappella* groups are on campus; the Meddiebempsters are the oldest.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Founded in the spring of 1937, the Meddies performed in USO shows after World War II.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin College signed onto the American College and University President's Climate Commitment in 2007.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The college followed through with a carbon neutrality plan released in 2009, with 2020 as the target year for carbon neutrality.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] According to the plan, general improvements to Maine's electricity grid will account for 7% of carbon reductions, commuting improvements will account for 1%, and the purchase of renewable energy credits will account for 41%.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In 2017, the college was on track to meet the 28% own source reduction target, and efforts have continued in the areas of energy conservation, efficiency upgrades and transitioning to lower carbon fuel sources.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin's facilities are heated by an on-campus heating plant that burns natural gas.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Between 2002 and 2008, Bowdoin College decreased its CO2 emissions by 40%.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] It achieved that reduction by switching from No.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] 2 oil in its heating plant, reducing the campus set heating point from 72 to 68 degrees, and by adhering to its own Green Design Standards in renovations.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In addition, Bowdoin runs a single stream recycling program, and its dining services department has begun composting food waste and unbleached paper napkins.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin received an overall "B−" grade for its sustainability efforts on the College Sustainability Report Card 2009 published by the Sustainable Endowments Institute.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In 2003, Bowdoin committed to achieving LEED-certification for all new campus buildings.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The college has since completed construction on Osher and West residency halls, the Peter Buck Center for Health & Fitness, the Sidney J.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Watson Arena, 216 Maine Street, and 52 Harpswell all of which have attained LEED, Silver LEED or Gold LEED certification.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The new dorms partially use collected rainwater as part of an advanced flushing system.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The new Park Row Apartments and Schiller Coastal Studies Center are Passive House Certified through Phius.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin College's main campus in Brunswick ranges over an area of 215 acres (87 ha) and includes 120 buildings, some of which date back to the 18th century.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Prominent buildings on the campus include the college's oldest building, Massachusetts Hall, the Parker Cleaveland House, and the Harriet Beecher Stowe House.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The campus has two museums: the Bowdoin College Museum of Art, in the Walker Art Building, and the Peary-MacMillan Arctic Museum, in the Gibbons Center for Arctic Studies.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The 118-acre (48 ha) Schiller Coastal Studies Center is located 8 miles (13 km) south of Orr's Island in Harpswell, Maine.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin College operates the Bowdoin Scientific Station on Kent Island in the Bay of Fundy in New Brunswick.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Organized athletics at Bowdoin began in 1828 with a gymnastics program established by the "father of athletics in Maine", John Neal.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] In the proceeding years, Neal agitated for more programs, and himself taught bowling, boxing, and other sports.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin College teams are known as the Polar Bears.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] They compete as a member of the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) Division III level, primarily competing in the New England Small College Athletic Conference (NESCAC), of which they were a founding member in 1971.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The mascot for all Bowdoin College athletic teams is the Polar bear, generally referred to in the plural, i.e., "The Polar Bears".
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The fight song, *Forward The White*, was composed by Kenneth A.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The college's rowing club competes in the Colby-Bates-Bowdoin Chase Regatta annually.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The rowing club also competes as a member of the American Collegiate Rowing Association; the women's team won its first national championship in 2023.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The field hockey team are four-time NCAA Division III National Champions; winning the title in 2007 (defeating Middlebury College), 2008 (defeating Tufts University), 2010 (defeating Messiah College), and 2013 (defeating Salisbury University).
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] The men's tennis team won the 2016 NCAA Division III Championship after defeating Emory University in Kalamazoo, Michigan.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Principal athletic facilities include Whittier Field (capacity: 9,000), Morrell Gymnasium (1,500), Sidney J.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Watson Arena (2,300), Pickard Fields, and the Buck Center for Health and Wellness.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin graduates have led all three branches of the American federal government, including both houses of Congress.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Franklin Pierce (1824) was America's fourteenth President; Melville Weston Fuller (1853) served as Chief Justice of the United States; Thomas Brackett Reed (1860) was twice elected Speaker of the House of Representatives; and Wallace H.
[src:bowdoin-college/bowdoin-college] Mitchell (1954) both served as Majority Leader of the United States Senate.
